The first virtual operator is already coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Probably
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer virtually all services as their partners in Western Europe.
However, here we still need something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
It's probably not going to be late.
That Czech operators are part of the most expensive of Europe, we have already written it on mobile.cz.
The rest also confirmed that the Czech Telecommunications Office (CHTU) warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is among the most expensive in the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the regulation of roaming rates, it is likely that there will be a paradox situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators sending SMS from abroad will be cheaper than if they send them from home.
How can prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared with Europe?
The answer is simple, lack of competence that you really want to fight.
This probably seems paradoxical to us, because we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that there is an extreme competition in the Czech market.
For this reason, the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (CTU), Pavel Dvořák, said that there is no longer room for any other operator in the Czech Republic.
It may be true that for a classic operator with their own network, you no longer have too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be hard to find some frequency).
However, there is still a possibility - the virtual operator.
Exactly the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market brought a significant price downturn to which classical operators should also react.
At the same time, even before the entry of sharks such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile to the Britain market, voices were heard both there and here.
It has been shown that there is a place for this type of operator and that they can succeed.
On the other hand, there is no need to look for examples too far away.
In February of this year, we informed you about the outside of the virtual Mobilking operator in Poland.
Only after half a year did this operator get over 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighbouring country.
On the other hand, after Mobilking, the Penta group is located which, apart from that, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:phone.
The advantage of virtual operators is to focus on many more concrete target groups.
In addition, for them to function effectively, they are enough with many less customers than a classic operator.
They do not bear relatively large costs in the construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world, this type of virtual operators are usually profiled with low costs - they offer cheap SMS calls and messages that often conflict with the provision of more adjusted services.
Thus, for example, Tesco mobile in Great Britain offers SMS at least half of the cost of competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a good blow to bet on a trivial target group.
This operator is specifically directed to man.
"The right man chooses Mobilking - is the operator that likes and who can be trusted," says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, who works this virtual operator.
It's hard to say if it looks like a concept that Poland could trap in our country.
Therefore, Vodafone spokesperson Miroslav Čepiký: "The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, from the point of view of the offer of services, it is relatively satisfied"
There is no possibility in the Czech Republic, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if there will be any virtual operator in the Czech Republic that will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the Czech Republic it does not seem too promising.
It is more about the launch of Mobilking in other countries of our region," said Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the Penta financial group.
It indirectly ensured that the current mobile telephony operators in the Czech Republic definitely did not get involved in this idea.
Instead, they try to do everything possible so that no potential competition can emerge.
Interest in the launch of a virtual mobile operator already shows that the Novera GTS group would like to take a step forward to become a real competition for Telefónica O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in this, in order to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telephone services but also mobile telephony.
And how much earlier, better.
With this possibility, we have repeatedly met with all the Czech mobile phone operators.
With some of them we have managed to move forward at the meetings," said the group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
Then maybe they're wasting better times.
It appears that, for non-official information, the first official operator would have to arrive by the end of the year.
But for now its appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"We now believe that the situation is ideal for the appearance of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market in comparison with others is a very specific market.
Until now no one has addressed us with any complex and serious project in this field," said Vlastimil Sršeně, spokesman for Telefónica O2.
The specificity of the Czech market concerns other operators.
The spokesman for T-mobile, Martina Kemrová, in accordance with the opinion of O2, adds: "To date we have not registered any viable commercial project which, bilaterally beneficial, can continue to develop."
And he adds: "In the T-Mobile network it will be difficult to find any virtual operator until the end of the year.
At this point, we should already have on the table a specific contract that could be studied in such short horizons."
Vodafone directs its attention rather to meeting the requirements of a 3G licence itself.
Miroslav Čepýký adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this concerns the distribution of expenditure and infrastructure.
We consider it to be the greatest contribution from the customers' point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this field is in the partner with whom to establish a network shared for a fast internet on the mobile."
Offices responsible - with nail and meat operators
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increasing competition which would lead to a lower price and thus to a lower profit.
Then why facilitate entry to competition?
When the operators want to get something, they are able to pull out of the same rope, proof of that is the grip when U:phone came out.
Perhaps the biggest pressure on ČTU was at the time of U:phone entry by the T-Mobile company.
This is certified by the public information available on the CTU website.
But right now U:fon serves as an argument why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds: "In addition, not long ago the competitive environment in the mobile telephony market was opened to a fourth operator.
With regard to the nature of the mobile telephony market in the Czech Republic, it is natural that the entry of another player into the market would be subject to him and, above all, to his great requirements."
This is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously discouraging because of the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
It is not just the position of the ČTU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in commercial tenders, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
This belongs purely to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Tenders (UOHS).
However, this expressed its typical attitude towards this problem.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile telephony market would be possible after a contract on the rental of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile telephony operator and a virtual operator is concluded.
To date, no agreement has been concluded as the offer of the potentials concerned was not sufficiently interesting for the classical operators," added Kristian Chalupa, of the Department of External Relations of the UOHS.
These statements are not surprising to the representatives of the operators.
For offices that must represent consumers' interests, this is more than a consideration, apart from that, they must note that no one takes advantage of their position on the market.
Especially when Kristian Chalupa adds: "In the foreign country where virtual operators normally operate, we can observe that their entry into the market contributed to the lower prices of mobile telephony services"
Obviously, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market media and the downturn in prices does not come within the interest of the UOHS.
The dramatic shock in all of this is in the dissonant reactions resulting from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether it is really a coincidence is offered on its own.
It is the same as the price of petrol in the gas pipelines as it is clear that it is the work of randomity and a hard struggle for competition.
"The Office in this regard has not found signs of disloyal competition and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators have a dominant position, therefore, do not have a corresponding rise in liability in their market operations.
The tools needed to open the mobile market to virtual operators are, rather, missing, as well as telecommunications regulators," added Chalupa.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of the many conflicting points.
There is, of course, a relevant market analysis developed by the CTU, whereby telecommunications is from the point of view of commercial tendering a single market.
In this kind of market, of course, none of the Czech operators have a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer another vision - for a virtual operator to emerge is always necessary the agreement with the network administrator.
And the mobile phone operator - with all its logic - has the monopoly of its network.
Therefore, in a specific segment it must be necessarily dominant.
And if this argument was not accepted, at least for ÚOHS, it should be a warning that three mobile operators appear to rise in a similar way.
Current complaints from stakeholders (including GTS Novera) show that many similar obstacles occur in all negotiations with operators.
Loading responsibility in ČTU is a fairly common trick in the telecommunications field of which ÚOHS washes hands in all this matter.
We've already met with him in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, a new amendment to the Telecommunications Act for the extension of CTU's competition in the field of commercial tenders which had not taken effect was introduced recently, even when a number of specialists promised that the situation would improve.
This must be fully known by the representatives of ÚOHS, but it is clear that their interests are elsewhere.
It's all right, when no one sees
At the same time, unexpectedly something as well as a pseudovirtual operator continues to work that in the Czech mobile networks already exist a few.
They are companies that place their own prices on mobile telephony services that, however, are only one part public.
These are usually companies dedicated to multi-level marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile telephony services.
Usually only a few selected get the price list of these companies.
The magic is that the company, with respect to the operator, acts as a classic business client of the same by charging a large number of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will then receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that commercial conditions in all Czech mobile telephony operators prohibit that type of return.
"If cases such as those mentioned could be found to be infraction under the terms of the contract that could be translated at the end of the partnership with the given society," answered Martina Kemrová's question about this problem.
But it is quite unlikely that this kind of activity by mobile telephony operators does not reach responsible people.
Exactly in the case of the three companies mentioned, there may be thousands of customers.
None of the operators are opposed to this procedure.
With the activities of these companies they gain no negligible profits and, at the same time, unlike the genuine virtual operators, they are in no way threatening their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepíký warns us of the possible problems: "the law allows a speculation of this kind, however, the services of this company are used only by a surprising percentage of customers.
These must also accept that your phone’s SIM card is not your name, so you cannot have it at all as a normal customer of operators.”
This is exactly what should seem to the least strange CTU.
There is also a new question for the ÚOHS.
If mobile telephony operators surround their eyes in this kind of procedure, why do they block the virtual operator's entry?
It is necessary to add that UOHS has sufficient competence to discover this type of activity and, if it is not to be desired, it should not be satisfied with the operator's explanations that they have no idea of this story and that their commercial conditions do not allow it.
When will we stop being the most expensive
As already clear in the text, the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market brought a significant drop in service prices.
At the same time, practically in all countries where the virtual operator emerged, classical operators tried to protect themselves from this disruption.
The arguments used by these were practically all identical - too small, a market, possibly too saturated, problems with the quality of the service, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, the regulatory bodies have now intervened and in none of the cases defended operators but their clients.
Both formal measures or informal pressure enabled the first virtual operator to emerge and with him they began to emerge more.
Unfortunately, the Czech Regulatory Body all this happens as if it were a burning key.
For our experience, we cannot help but be impressed that the confusion of the attributes in these cases suits them.
But we won't be disappointed.
If this information is correct between builders and the virtual operator actually reaches these lands, then the Czech mobile phone market is likely to start moving again.
If any of the operators allows any virtual mobile telephony operator to enter, it will be difficult for the UOHS to remain indifferent to the refusal (discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And we may stop calling more expensive than the rest of Europe.
