Hema-Quebec celebrated yesterday his 10th anniversary of his foundation, and his president, Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, because Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, he regained the confidence of the public that had been seriously vacated by the scandal of blood contaminated in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated by the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this drama and public discontent, the Government of Canada conducted a public survey in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horacio Krever, which intended to clarify the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations so that such a disaster would no longer occur.
While Judge Krever was delaying his relationship, certain provinces then set up a committee aimed at planning a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee carried out this mission.
As a result of the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Hema-Québec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to provide all other provinces and territories.
" In 1998, when Hema-Québec began its activities, nearly 38 per cent of the people still trusted in the blood system in Quebec, Decary recalled.
The situation was discouraging.
After having made many efforts to improve the safety of blood products and much work during the years that followed, we have regained public confidence ", he said before proudly that at the beginning of 2008, approximately 94% of the Quebec population had confidence in Hema-Québec.
Dr. Décary recalls, however, that " confidence is extremely fragile " .
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, we attended in Europe the birth of numerous cases of the human variant of the disease of the loca cow, a new variant of the disease of Creutzfeldt-Jakob, account Decary.
And we didn't know if this disease could be transmitted by blood.
Then we support one of the main recommendations of Krever and Gélineau's reports, according to which when we don't know, and when a serious illness can arise from that, in this case, the Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, we introduce exclusion measures.
In April 1999, we denied the blood of those who had remained in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
But a few years ago, it has been demonstrated beyond any doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode showed us that the precautionary principle applied had meaning."
In 1999, a much more sensitive HIV detection technique appeared on the market: nuclear acid tests that enable donors to directly detect the presence of the virus and not the presence of antibodies to the virus, on which the tests used so far were based.
Nuclear acid tests have allowed the period between the time the person has been infected and the time the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
We were able to reduce this period for less than a week.
We have thus substantially reduced the risk that certain donors are infected without knowing it and that we cannot detect them.
These improvements significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS by a blood transfusion.
Today, a person every 12 million lives at the risk of receiving HIV - contaminated blood.
"This means that you will have to distribute 12 million blood products before someone is infected by HIV.
Thus, since Hema-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, more than 24 years will pass before a case of HIV transmission occurs for a blood product.
I think it is possible today to receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to recover health without concern," says Hema-Québec's head of management.
" Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
It's never known which pathogen could emerge in the system.
Last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of the Meeting, which, for example, the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
It must be constantly vigilant " , Mr. Décary continues before stressing that, in addition to a secure supply, Hema-Québec should also provide sufficient supplies.
" The needs increase because the population is ageing.
Since more aggressive anti-cancer treatments, patients often require injection of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences on the network of blood donors that regroup in the medium term only 3 per cent of Quebecs eligible for blood donation. "
All persons with good health, aged 18 and who meet the eligibility criteria may, however, give blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On the average, 14% of those who propose their blood are not accepted because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they travel in a country where malaria rules, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
" With this 3%, we have managed to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Grief is very rare.
But there is a need to renew the members of this donor network as they age and cannot give their blood any more.
But it is difficult to convince people to give their blood, but above all, to hold them and encourage them to be regular donors.
Since the present life is very distraught, we rarely find time to spend an hour to give her blood," says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec provides not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone inerts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that are almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public blood bank of the umbilical cord in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was previously considered as biomedical waste is full of a blood-rich mother cells that can be used to treat serious diseases such as leukemia.
" We celebrated a few weeks ago, placing it in the bank of our thousandth blood sample of the umbilical cord and is expected to extract more than a thousand of these per year.
We should begin to propose it for injections at the beginning of next year," says Dr. Decary, who describes this blood supply program as very popular.
" Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot enjoy this " since Hema-Québec has no resources to propose this complex and costly program in all Quebec hospitals.
