The Smart Car Imitates the Abeyro Flight
What would be the best way to develop technologies in order to avoid collisions, if not the imitation of existing barriers sensors in nature?
For example, that of the Aborigines.
In a surprising project presented at the CEATEC in Japan, the aberrants gave the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision prevention systems.
Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the robotic driving system of nature-like BR23C cars, which was given the characteristics of the aliens, with the ultimate goal of creating a system that can exacerbate all collisions.
During the flight, each abeyorro creates its own private oval space that actually looks a lot like our protective safety capsule - explained in the Kazuhhiro Doi exhibition, the technology director of RP and development and research.
They play an important role in the composite eyes of the aliens who are able to see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees.
To copy the compound eye function, engineers used the laser beam length measurement system.
This identifies the obstacles ahead of the BR23C within a distance of 2 metres, at an angle of 180 degrees, calculates its distance and sends a signal to the vehicle microprocessor which is immediately transformed into a manoeuvre to avoid collision.
In a fraction of seconds, the obstacle is identified, then the vehicle robot imitating the movements of the aliens, altering the direction turning the wheels to the necessary extent.
Unlike any existing system at present, this manoeuvre is totally instinctive.
"If not, the vehicle robot could not react quickly enough as to avoid obstacles" - says Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the vehicle robot project.
It must react immediately and instinctively, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the protective safety capsule, within which all types of collisions are currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what an outsider does to fool other aliens.
This process must be performed in an open and close eyes.
However, unlike the Aborigines, the movement cannot be directed upward, downward or diagonal, but can only be bidimensional and exclusively in the direction of rotation of the wheels
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for the Aborigines to mislead other Aborigines, here they used only as a possibility for the robot of the car the rotating movement and the acceleration plus the braking.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and greater their energy density, which means they have a longer life than the lithium-ion.
According to Andoh, the important is the instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the data processing capacity, or much less the storage capacity.
This device must only process some input signals in each second and react as appropriate.
It is not necessary to store this data or react with an instinctive logic based on the data of previous maneuvers, so it only uses a few dozen kilobytes of memory.
You don't need gigabytes or megabytes.
This is the first step in developing technology to immediately remove obstacles, which, according to Nissan's calculations, can be incorporated into the models produced in series within 10 years.
Another possibility for your application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to his destination, avoiding the existing obstacles on his way.
