Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008, national industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent compared to last month's prices and by 12.9 per cent compared to August 2007 prices - reported by the Central Statistics Office (CSH).
Export prices increased by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008 and decreased by 3.9 per cent compared to the previous year.
As a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent over the previous month and by 3.2 per cent over the previous year.
Industrial sales prices increased only to a minimum, with 0.1 per cent.
The domestic sales prices of the processing industry increased by at least 0.1 per cent in July.
The higher price increases occurred in August 2008 in the leather and footwear production sector (2.8 per cent), primarily due to the 4.6 per cent monthly increase in bags and belts and the 2.5 per cent increase in footwear.
The highest price level of basic plastic and chemical materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical production branch (1.6 per cent).
There was a decrease in prices in the petrochemical sector, (1.4 per cent), in the production of electric machines and instruments (0.9 per cent), as well as - to a minimum extent - in the processing sectors of wood (0.1 per cent).
They did not change the prices of paper production, editorials and prints.
In the rest of the processing industry, there was an increase in prices between 0.2 and 0.9 per cent.
In the supply of electricity, gas, heat and water that represent an important weight within domestic trade, an increase of 0.3 per cent was recorded in August, first of all due to the effect of the increase in official prices from the first of July.
In a 12-month comparison - in domestic sales of the processing industry - the higher price increase was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4 per cent).
In the metalmaking sector, an increase of 13.2 per cent was observed, while in the food, drink and tobacco industry there was an increase of 11 per cent.
There was a decrease in prices in the textile industry (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of electric machines and instruments (0.3 per cent).
In the rest of the processing sectors, the rate of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 per cent.
During the year in the processing industry, prices increased globally by 10.2 per cent.
Electricity prices, gas, heat and water supply exceeded by 18.7 per cent of the prices of the previous year.
In August, among the various sectors of domestic trade, the highest monthly price increase (0.7 per cent) was recorded in the investment goods sectors.
In the consumer sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, in the energy and intermediate sectors prices did not change compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, with respect to the same month of the previous year, the higher price increases occurred in the energy sectors and in the intermediate industry (16.8 per cent).
In the producer branches of consumer goods, a drop of 6.8 per cent was recorded and in the investment assets was 1.4 per cent.
The export prices of the industry calculated in HUF increased by 1.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and compared to 12 months, there was a decrease of 3.9 per cent.
The rate of our national currency in one month was reduced by 1.7 per cent with respect to the euro and by 7.1 per cent with respect to the dollar, compared to August 2007, it strengthened by 7.5 per cent with respect to the euro and 15.9 per cent with respect to the dollar.
