Today the European Summit for Equal Opportunities has been launched in Paris, its host is France that this year is also President of the European Union.
Lívia Járóka, Member of the European People's Party by Fidesz, in his full-fledged message, as one of the main speakers of this professional meeting, drew attention to segregation in education, because it is one of the most serious violations affecting Roma children and is also the biggest obstacle to the prevalence of their interests.
This high-level conference was opened - on behalf of the French Presidency - by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs and by Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner for Employment, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
Representatives of governments, European social partners and representatives of the most important European social rights protection organizations attended the meeting.
Járóka - according to the press office of the Fidesz group of Members in the European Parliament - warned that, in addition to discrimination in employment, the gypsies remain outside the labour market primarily because of their low level of education.
"Most of the young gypsies have not completed secondary education and due to the poor quality of basic education, only a minor part can obtain university diploma."
Jaróka also stressed that education, as a fundamental human right, has a decisive role in the prevalence of other human rights as well.
Investment in the education of Roma children at an early age can strengthen the economy of the Member States of the European Union.
According to the Euro MP, it is necessary to raise these issues widely between both the gypsies and the non gypsies.
As early as the school begins, a gypsum student will have more opportunities to become an active member of the labour market; through income and consumption taxes they will also contribute to the national budget.
"Gitanians, as citizens of the European Union, must ensure their right to quality education and ensure the abolition of segregated and low-level education," said Lívia Járóka.
According to the Euro MP, the objective and active unit of the European Union is needed to speed up the process of school disengagement immediately, so it is essential that the existing and planned anti-discrimination directives are properly implemented.
"There is a need to break the vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment, to offer the opportunity for Roma children to guarantee the democratic space so that they can contribute to the future of Europe as citizens of full rights," Járóka demanded.
The objective of the European Summit on Equal Opportunities organised annually since last year's Berlin meeting, which was held in the sign of the "European Year of Equal Opportunities", is to ensure a unique forum to promote the abolition of discrimination and equal opportunities at European and national level in the Member States.
