Goodbye to the old cinema Paradise, the cities cancel the historic halls
Historical cinematographic rooms close in favor of the Multiplex.
"A city without cinematographic rooms in a blind city is like a face without eyes."
The image offered by Director Giuseppe Tornatore photographes effectively what is happening in the large Italian urban centres and also in the provincial cities.
The process of marginalization of the cinemas, which with the birth of the great meticians in the periphery and the consequent disappearance of the mono rooms in the central areas of the city, is an inevitable and indisputable event with all the features of a true cultural crime.
To disappear are almost always historical places, full of memory," it is as if a friend died, a well-known person with whom a piece of place and so much emotion was shared," notes the director of the new movie Paradise, the film that was twenty years ago won the first Oscar and the grand jury award to Cannes, who had the poetry of a movie room in the province and nostalgia in the way of living the film that was lost perhaps forever.
The figures given by the Anec, the main association of traders, are clear: in the last five years 316 traditional cinemas have been closed, and to pay most are mainly the rooms of the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most suffering from closures are the first, Emilia-Romania with 82 less cinemas, following Tuscany (44) and Lombardia (41).
It is a demonstration that the responsible for its disappearance is the adventure of the multiplex, these three Italian regions themselves that have recorded the largest number of new methic cinemas: 195 screens but in Lombardia in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany than in Emilia-Romema.
“Italian exercise has been unreasonably developed” notes Paolo Protti, president of Anec, “it would be useful for new structures to be built but it would be necessary to ensure the survival of those already existing, because when a city hall closes, not all of its members are willing to transfer to the mechanics.
Not to mention the lack of funds for traders: the previous debt of the state is approximately EUR 10 million.
It is shameful from an ethical and moral point of view that the government does not respect the laws that exist.
To support the sector, between EUR 16 and 18 million per year would be used."
Interestingly for the case of Bologna, the first Italian city concerned about the closures, decided to repair itself with the signature of a protocol between the municipality and Anec, the first of this type in Italy to promote and protect the cinema mono room either in the historical centre or in the periphery.
The proposed rules include means of tax facilitation in favour of managers and advantages for the public in terms of mobility: viewers can enter the restricted area of traffic and have special parking rates.
"It is an initiative that I like" observes Giuseppe Tornatore, and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by introducing other measures.
It is true that in contrast to the extra power of the mechanics, the traditional rooms need to improve the quality of sound and image because the public today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that was always important to me: the closure of the movies in Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to carry out the "New Paradise cinema", which I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I've been living in Rome for 25 years, and when I go through the Rialto or the National Road Quirinale already closed, where I've lived so many shared emotions, not to see the dusty cartels, I turn to the other side.”
